1. CSS Basics

•	What is CSS?
  o	CSS = Cascading Style Sheets.
  o	Analogy: If HTML is the "skeleton" (structure), CSS is the "skin/clothing" (style/appearance).

•	Syntax:

  selector {
      property: value;
  }

  o	Selector: The HTML element you want to style (e.g., h1, .my-class, #my-id).
  o	Declaration: The rule applied (e.g., color: red;).

•	How to add CSS:
1.	Inline: Inside the HTML tag (e.g., <h1 style="color:blue;">). Not recommended.
2.	Internal: Inside <style> tags in the HTML <head>.
3.	External (Best Practice): Create a .css file (e.g., style.css) and link it in your HTML head:

HTML
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

________________________________________

2. Colors & Backgrounds

•	Color Values:
  o	Named Colors: red, blue, gold.
  o	Hex Codes: #RRGGBB (e.g., #000000 is black).
  o	RGB: rgb(255, 0, 0) (Red, Green, Blue values 0-255).
  o	RGBA: rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.5) (Adds Alpha for transparency, 0.0 to 1.0).
  o	HSL: hsl(0, 100%, 50%) (Hue, Saturation, Lightness).

•	Backgrounds:
  o	background-color: Sets the background color.
  o	background-image: Sets an image (url('image.jpg')).
  o	background-repeat: no-repeat (prevents tiling), repeat-x, repeat-y.
  o	background-position: center, top, left.
  o	background-size: cover (fills area, may crop), contain (shows full image).

________________________________________

3. Typography (Fonts)

•	font-family: Specifies the font (e.g., "Times New Roman", sans-serif). Always list a fallback font.

•	font-size: px (pixels), em (relative to parent), rem (relative to root html).

•	font-weight: Thickness of text (bold or numbers like 400, 700).

•	font-style: Used mostly for italic.

•	text-align: left, center, right.

________________________________________

4. The Box Model (Borders, Margins, Padding)

Every HTML element is a rectangular "box".
•	Borders:
  o	Syntax: border: width style color;
  o	Example: border: 2px solid black;
  o	border-radius: Rounds corners. 50% makes a square element a perfect circle.

•	Margins: Space outside the border (pushes neighbors away).
  o	Margin Collapse: Vertical margins of adjacent elements overlap; the larger margin wins (they don't add up).
  o	margin: auto; centers a block element horizontally.

•	Padding: Space inside the border (between border and content).

•	Shadows:
  o	box-shadow: 5px 5px 10px gray; (x-offset, y-offset, blur, color).
  o	text-shadow: Same concept but for text.

________________________________________

5. Layout & Positioning

•	display property:
  o	block: Takes full width, starts on new line (e.g., <div>, <h1>).
  o	inline: Takes only needed width, no new line (e.g., <span>, <a>). Width/height settings don't work.
  o	inline-block: Flows like text (inline) but respects width/height.
  o	none: Hides element completely (removes from document flow).

•	position property:
  o	static (Default): Normal flow.
  o	relative: Offset from its normal position (using top, left), but gap remains in flow.
  o	absolute: Removed from flow; positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor.
  o	fixed: Stuck to the browser window (stays visible when scrolling).
  o	sticky: Acts like relative until you scroll past it, then becomes fixed.

•	Float:
  o	float: left/right: Pushes element to side; text wraps around it.
  o	clear: both: Forces an element to drop below floating elements.

•	Overflow:
  o	Handles content that is too big for its container.
  o	hidden (clips content), scroll (adds scrollbars), auto.

________________________________________

6. Advanced Selectors

•	Combinators:
    o	Descendant (space): div p (All <p> inside <div>).
    o	Child (>): div > p (Direct children only).
    o	Adjacent Sibling (+): div + p (The <p> immediately after <div>).
    o	General Sibling (~): div ~ p (All <p> after <div>).

•	Pseudo-classes: (State of an element)
  o	:hover: Mouse over.
  o	:active: Click and hold.
  o	:focus: Element selected (like an input).
  o	:nth-child(even/odd): Great for striping tables.

•	Pseudo-elements: (Specific parts)
  o	::before / ::after: Inserts content via CSS.
  o	::first-letter: Styles the first letter of a block.

________________________________________

7. Flexbox (Modern Layout)

The most important layout tool.

•	Container: display: flex;

•	Direction: flex-direction: row (default, horizontal) or column (vertical).

•	Main Axis Alignment (Justify):
  o	justify-content: center; (Centers items).
  o	justify-content: space-between; (Even spacing, pushed to edges).

•	Cross Axis Alignment (Align):
  o	align-items: center; (Centers items vertically in a row).

•	Wrapping: flex-wrap: wrap; (Items drop to next line if no space).

________________________________________

8. Motion (Transform & Animation)

•	Transformations: (Instant change)
  o	transform: translate(x, y); (Move).
  o	transform: rotate(45deg); (Spin).
  o	transform: scale(1.5); (Zoom).
  o	transform: skew(20deg); (Distort).

•	Animations: (Change over time)
  1.	Define Keyframes:
  CSS
  @keyframes mySlide {
      from { left: 0px; }
      to { left: 100px; }
  }
  2.	Apply to element:
  CSS
  .box {
      animation-name: mySlide;
      animation-duration: 2s;
      animation-iteration-count: infinite; /* or specific number */
      animation-timing-function: linear; /* or ease-in-out */
  }
